The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	Melbourne, March 4 (PTI): The government of Victoria today announced that people caught carrying knives and prohibited weapons in public areas will be fined $1,000 on the spot.           
	The government of the Australian state that has seen a spate of attacks on Indians has granted special powers to police to conduct random weapon searches. Under a three-point plan, minors will be banned from buying prohibited or controlled weapons.                   
	New Delhi(PTI): Uttar Pradesh has topped a list of states and Union territories with 900 child-rape cases in 2008 in a survey conducted by the home ministry. Madhya Pradesh and Maharashtra follow with 892 and 690 cases. Bengal had 129 such cases in between 2006 and 2008.                  
	New Delhi (PTI): Maoist leader Khobad Ghandy moved a court on Thursday seeking copies of some documents and CDs that Delhi police had used to chargesheet him in February. The CDs show him addressing armed Maoist cadres in Nepal.                  
	New Delhi (PTI): Over 29,000 personnel of the central police organisations have either resigned or sought voluntary retirement in the last three years, with the highest attrition rate being in 2009. As many as 6,537 personnel have resigned from the Border Security Force. The paramilitary forces have also seen a steady increase in such cases.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI):The ministry of social justice has announced an award for the best website for the disabled. It will be given on December 3, the International Day of Disabled Persons. The ministrys own website provides features like screenreading and voice-recognition software.                   
	Srinagar (PTI): A Haryana couple working in a Kendriya Vidyalaya in Budgam in Jammu and Kashmir were found dead under mysterious circumstances in their air force quarters on Thursday, police said.                                                                                                                                              
